      "url": "https://cdn.misoenergy.org/2026-02-13_Docket%20No.%20ER26-1397-000741977.pdf",
      "title": "[PDF] February 13, 2026 VIA ELECTRONIC FILING The Honorable ...",
      "published_date": "2026-02-13T00:00:00.000Z",
      "text": "Madison Pitts \nCorporate Counsel \nDirect Dial: 317-316-7911 \nEmail: mpitts@misoenergy.org \n\nFebruary 13, 2026\n\nVIA ELECTRONIC FILING\n\nThe Honorable Debbie-Anne Reese \nSecretary \nFederal Energy Regulatory Commission \n888 First Street, N.E \nWashington, D.C. 20246 \n\nRe: Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. Docket No. ER26-____-000 Surplus Interconnection Service Improvements\n\nDear Secretary Reese:\n\nThe Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”) hereby submits 1proposed revisions to its Attachment X Generator Interconnection Procedures (“Attachment X”) of its Open Access Transmission Tariff (“Tariff”) to improve its Surplus Interconnection Service process. MISO proposes to impose certain guardrails that improve the efficiency of the surplus interconnection process, including limitations on when surplus Interconnection Requests can be submitted, how Material Modifications requests are managed while surplus Interconnection Requests are pending, increased deposit requirements, and the creation of a defined term to describe a Generating Facility with Surplus Interconnection Service. This filing is consistent with and accomplishes the purpose of Order 2023. 2 As explained below, MISO requests that the proposed revisions be made effective as of April 15, 2026, which is at least sixty (60) days after filing.\n\nI. BACKGROUND\n\nA. MISO’s Net Zero Interconnection Service\n\nBefore Surplus Interconnection Service was adopted by the Commission, MISO proposed its predecessor, “Net Zero Interconnection Service.” 3 Based on concepts used in a filed and accepted LGIA, Net Zero Interconnection Service was proposed “in response to several requests\n\n1 MISO makes this filing pursuant to section 205 of the Federal Power Act (“FPA”), 16 U.S.C. § 824d, and Part 35 \nof the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission’s (“FERC” or “Commission”) regulations, 18 C.F.R. § 35.0 et seq. \n(2022). All capitalized terms in this filing that are not otherwise defined have the same meaning as they have \nunder the current MISO Tariff. \n2 Improvements to Generator Interconnection Procedures and Agreements, Order Nos. 2023 & 2023-A, 184 FERC \n¶ 61,054 (2023), order on reh’g and clarification, 186 FERC ¶ 61,199 (2024) (together, “Order No. 2023”). \n3 Midwest Indep. Transmission Sys. Operator, 138 FERC ¶ 61,233 (2012) (“Net Zero Order”). \nThe Honorable Debbie-Anne Reese \nFebruary 13, 2026 \nPage 2 \n\nto connect generation and run when existing generators were not running.” 4 Thus, Net Zero Interconnection Service allowed an Interconnection Customer “to increase the gross generating capability at the point of interconnection of an existing generating facility without increasing the net generation output at the point of interconnection above the existing generating facility’s capability, thereby permitting a new generating facility to interconnect at that point.” 5 A sub-class of Energy Resource Interconnection Service (“ERIS”), Net Zero Interconnection Service allowed an existing generator and a new generator to control the output of both units where the net effect on the system was zero. 6\n\nMISO introduced two (2) additional agreements to ensure the Existing Generating Facility maintained its “net zero” effect on the Transmission System. The first of these agreements was the Energy Displacement Agreement. An Interconnection Customer would execute an Energy Displacement Agreement before it submitted a request for Net Zero Interconnection Service if said Interconnection Customer was not the owner or the subsidiary owner of the Existing Generating Facility. 7 The second agreement, called the Monitoring and Consent Agreement, was entered with the applicable Transmission Owner and “would govern Net Zero Interconnection Service and maintain output within the parameters of the G[enerator] I[nterconnection A[greement](‘GIA’).” 8 If either agreement was not executed prior to the execution of the GIA, the Net Zero Interconnection Service request was deemed withdrawn. 9\n\nAlthough the Commission recognized the benefits of Net Zero Interconnection Service, the Commission directed MISO to modify its proposal to “implement additional procedures that ensure that Net Zero Interconnection Service is offered on a fair, transparent, and non discriminatory basis[.]” 10 Specifically, the Commission identified concerns related to study assumptions during off-peak conditions, potential impacts on competition, and a lack of transparency regarding available Net Zero Interconnection opportunities. 11 After several compliance filings, the Commission accepted MISO’s proposal in 2015. 12\n\nB. Orders No. 845 and 845-A\n\nIn 2017, the Commission issued a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking to revise its pro forma Large Generator Interconnection Procedures and pro forma Large Generator Interconnection Agreement to improve certainty for Interconnection Customers, promote more informed\n\n4 Transmittal Letter, Docket No. ER12-309-000 at 7 (filed November 1, 2011) (“Net Zero Transmittal Letter”). \n5 Net Zero Order at P 16. \n6 Id. \n7 Net Zero Order at P 255. \n8 Net Zero Transmittal Letter at 8. \n9 Id. \n10 Net Zero Order at P 302. \n11 Net Zero Order at P 30. \n12 Notational Order, Docket No. ER12-309-007 (FERC delegated order Dec. 4, 2015). \n\ninterconnections, and enhance the interconnection process. Among these reforms, the Commission proposed “a requirement that Transmission Providers provide an expedited process for Interconnection Customers to utilize or transfer surplus interconnection service at [an] Existing Generating Facility.” 13 Order Nos. 845 and 845-A 14 subsequently directed transmission providers to adopt and develop, among other processes, Surplus Interconnection Service.\n\nAs noted by the Commission, the Surplus Interconnection Service process, like Net Zero Interconnection Service, allowed an Interconnection Customer to utilize the unneeded portion of an existing interconnection customer’s interconnection service. 15 Thus Surplus Interconnection Service contained many of the same process requirements and limitations as Net Zero Interconnection Service: Surplus Interconnection Service required transmission providers to perform reactive power, short circuit/fault duty, and stability analysis studies in addition to steady state analyses as necessary to ensure all reliability conditions are met and to ensure reliable use of surplus interconnections service. 16 Although the Commission ultimately did not maintain its open solicitation process for Surplus Interconnection Service, the Commission maintained a less stringent requirement for Transmission Providers to give preferential access to affiliates of the existing interconnection customer and allow the transfer of surplus interconnection service if the interconnection customer or its affiliates decline to use it. 17 While the Commission declined to adopt pro forma Monitoring and Consent Agreements or Energy Displacement Agreements, the Commission required Transmission Provider to develop agreements “to establish conditions such as the term of operation, the interconnection service limit, and the mode of operation for energy production (i.e., common or singular operation) and to establish the roles and responsibilities of the parties for maintaining the operation of the facility within the parameters of the surplus interconnection service agreement.” 18\n\nIn 2019, MISO filed a partial compliance filing to specifically develop a Surplus Interconnection service Process. 19 MISO proposed to maintain much of its already-existing Net Zero Interconnection Service process but renamed the product “Surplus Interconnection Service.” MISO modified surplus service by expanding its application to both ERIS and Network Resource Interconnection Service (“NRIS”). Consistent with the Commission’s laxed solicitation requirement, MISO removed all references to a competitive solicitation process. Notably, MISO proposed to collect a $60,000 study deposit from surplus Interconnection Customers",
